<DOC><DOCNO> AP880615-0264 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0942EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a PM-ReligionRoundup Adv17   06-15 0576</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Religion Roundup, Adv 17,0597</SECOND><NOTE>$adv17</NOTE><NOTE>For release Fri PMs June 17, or thereafter</NOTE><DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The chief executive of the WorldCouncil of Churches recently offered some sharp criticisms of TVpreacher Jimmy Swaggart _ but not over the sexual exploits that gothim defrocked.   The Rev. Emilio Castro, an Uruguayan Methodist minister and thecouncil's general secretary, speaking at an ecumenical gatheringhere in May, had this to say about Swaggart's preaching abroad:   ``If someone was thinking of giving $10 to Jimmy Swaggart andasked my opinion, I would say for my country, his ministry is adisaster.''   Castro said Swaggart, through his support for the militarygovernment of Chile and apartheid government of South Africa, isharming the cause of Christ and ``scandalizing Christian people.''</TEXT><DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Representatives from six Baptistdenominations met in this city where their faith was founded inAmerica to celebrate the 350th anniversary of that beginning.   The Rev. Dwight M. Lundgren, senior minister of the FirstBaptist Church where the commemoration and a three-day conferenceon religious liberty were held early in June, said: ``We want toremind both other Baptists and the general public that to beBaptist has meant to be free and to safeguard the freedom of othersin their beliefs.''   The church, considered the first Baptist congregation inAmerica, was established in 1638 by religious dissenter RogerWilliams, who came to Providence after fleeing religiouspersecution in England and Massachusetts.</TEXT><DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-daySaints (Mormon) says ``one clearly understandable and divinelygiven rule would do more than all else to check'' the AIDSepidemic: ``Chastity before marriage and total fidelity inmarriage.''   In a statement on AIDS, the church's first presidency said ``ourconcern for the bitter fruit of sin is coupled with Christlikesympathy for its victims... We should reach out with kindness andcomfort to the afflicted, ministering to their needs and assistingthem with their problems.''</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Catholic Relief Services is expanding itshumanitarian assistance program in Nicaragua with the aid of a $3million grant from the U.S. government.   The grant will provide medicines and medical supplies to 205,000people, most of them children, at 80 clinics operated by Catholicchurches throughout the country, CRS said.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Jewish leader says commercial surrogateparenting is ``similar to baby selling'' and dehumanizes women by``placing a contractual price tag on human reproduction.''   ``Such arrangements put children at risk, and are not in theirbest interest,'' says Rabbi James Rudin, interreligious affairsdirector of the American Jewish Committee.   Rudin, member of a New York State Task Force on Life and theLaw, made his comments after the task force recommnded legislationdiscouraging surrogacy and allowing such arrangements only so longas no fee was paid.</TEXT><DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Smaller proportions of people havepreferences for mainline denominations than was the case in the1960's and mid-1970's, says the Religious Research Center.   It says a poll of 14,147 adults show these declines inpercentage expressing preferences for various major denominations:   For Methodists, now 9 percent, down from 11 percent in 1976; forLutherans, now 6 percent, down from 7 percent in l976; forPresbyterians, now 3 percent, down from 5 percent in l976; forEpiscopalians, now 2 percent, down from 3.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs June 17</NOTE></DOC>